posts.body:
You're right that he's at best a centrist and he has some either suspicious or naive attitudes, but you are misrepresenting some some things and quoting some things he said out of context. He's right that ZeroNet's current design has many issues with it that nofish has been slow to fix. This is not something he has mentioned, but for example, allowing sites to create new auth_addresses has been requested by Millchan's developer to make his anonymous posting functionality possible, and nofish made a comment on it but nothing ever came out of that. And although it wasn't his point when he made the spam (I agree he probably did it as both a power grab), one person with a Python script shouldn't be able to take down Tor registration.
>One anon discovered in folder /data/filters of Krixano zite http://127.0.0.1:43110/kxonet.bit/?/create-id three files: anti_jew.json, anti_lgbt.json, license_offending.json.
Actually, the blocklist is part of kxonet.bit, which includes many services besides ID creation, including those blacklists. As far as I know, Krixano wouldn't be able to force users of the KXoID service to subscribe to those blacklists (although yes, obviously it casts suspicion on Krixano of being a leftist jew and so on).
>"The code that registers (KxoID) users is in 0background.py, and yes, that one can be controlled by Krixano (or those who have the keys, right, e.g. me). "
That script is run on a Python sandbox which is supposed to prevent access to any dangerous functions beyond the normal ZeroID javascript API. The method used is a little sketchy from the engineering perspective, but so far I haven't been able to come up with any possible exploits with the conceptual understanding of how the sandbox works, although I haven't actually audited the code.
>"That's right, plugins can be unsafe."
The point of plugins is that they can extend ZeroID in arbitrary ways, so it's close to impossible to make them run safely. 0background.py is not a plugin, it's a BackgroundProcessing script.
>his need for coloboration in Zeronet development
In the "roll call" thread he implied he's going to fork ZeroNet. We'll have to see whether that will be a good or a bad thing in the long run.

4chan is still one of the sites I use the most on the Internet after 8 went down. I don't post because of the privacy concerns, only lurk using Tor Browser.
The sheer volume of posts means that even if 99% of everything posted is shit, most of the times I check in there will be at least one interesting thread in the catalog. And also there's a lot of interesting information on the archives. 4plebs publishes db dumps, I downloaded one to have in case the Internet goes down. But I still gotta figure out how to access it, I guess I would have to install FoolFuuka.
Unfortunately I don't know of any publicly available 8chan db dump. It seems the only way to get the old posts would be through scraping the Wayback Machine.
